                <div style="padding:20px 24px;">
                  <div class="topic-block">
                    <h4>Types of Electrical Conduit</h4>
                    <p>Conduits protect wiring from physical damage and provide a neat, organized pathway. The PEC specifies maximum support spacing for each type.</p>
                  </div>
                  <div class="conduit-compare">
                    <div class="conduit-card">
                      <h5>&#9881; EMT (Electrical Metallic Tubing)</h5>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Thin-walled rigid metal (steel or aluminum)</li>
                        <li>Used where physical protection is needed</li>
                        <li>Common in commercial and industrial settings</li>
                        <li><strong>PEC strap spacing:</strong> Max 900 mm (3 m near fittings)</li>
                        <li>Connected using compression or setscrew couplings</li>
                        <li>Cannot be used underground without protection</li>
                      </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="conduit-card">
                      <h5>&#11835; PVC / UPVC Conduit</h5>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Non-metallic (polyvinyl chloride)</li>
                        <li>Lightweight, corrosion-resistant</li>
                        <li>Common in residential and wet locations</li>
                        <li><strong>PEC support spacing:</strong> Max 900 mm</li>
                        <li>Joined using PVC solvent cement and couplings</li>
                        <li>UV-resistant UPVC used for outdoor exposed runs</li>
                      </ul>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                  <div class="info-box blue" style="margin-top:6px;">
                    <span class="ib-icon">&#8505;</span>
                    <div><strong>Conduit Bending — PEC Rules:</strong> The PEC specifies a minimum bend radius to prevent conductor insulation damage. For EMT, bends must not reduce the internal diameter. A <strong>conduit bender (hickey)</strong> is used for 90° stub-ups and offset bends. No more than four 90° bends (360° total) are permitted between pull boxes.</div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

