                  <div>
                    <span class="session-label">Topic 1</span>
                    <h2>Wire Pulling and Stripping</h2>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div style="padding:20px 24px;">
                  <div class="topic-block">
                    <h4>Wire Pulling Using Fish Tape</h4>
                    <p>A <strong>fish tape</strong> (also called a draw wire or pull wire) is a flat, flexible steel or fiberglass ribbon used to thread wires through conduit. The wire is attached to the end of the fish tape and pulled through as the tape is retracted.</p>
                    <ul>
                      <li>Always use pulling lubricant (wire lube) for long runs or multiple conductors</li>
                      <li>Pull from one end while a helper feeds wire at the other end</li>
                      <li>Do not exceed the maximum fill capacity of the conduit (40% fill for 3+ conductors per PEC)</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                  <div class="topic-block" style="margin-top:16px;">
                    <h4>Wire Stripping — Correct Procedure</h4>
                    <p>Proper wire stripping is critical for safe and reliable terminal connections:</p>
                    <table class="data-table" style="margin-top:10px;">
                      <thead>
                        <tr><th>Connection Type</th><th>Strip Length</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
                      </thead>
                      <tbody>
                        <tr>
                          <td>Screw terminals (outlets, switches)</td>
                          <td><strong>10–12 mm</strong></td>
                          <td>Form a clockwise loop around the screw shank</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                          <td>Push-in / stab-in connectors</td>
                          <td><strong>12–14 mm</strong></td>
                          <td>Insert straight; do not loop</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                          <td>Wire nuts / twist connectors</td>
                          <td><strong>20–25 mm</strong></td>
                          <td>Twist wires together before applying wire nut</td>
                        </tr>
                      </tbody>
                    </table>
                    <div class="info-box gold" style="margin-top:12px;">
                      <span class="ib-icon">&#9888;</span>
                      <div><strong>Critical:</strong> Never nick or score the copper conductor while stripping. Nicking reduces the conductor's cross-sectional area, creating a weak point that can overheat and fail. Use a proper wire stripper — never a knife blade on conductors.</div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <!-- Termination Rules -->
              <div class="card">
                <div class="section-header">
                  <div class="section-num">2</div>
                  <div>
                    <span class="session-label">Topic 2</span>
                    <h2>Termination Rules &amp; Color Coding</h2>
                  </div>
