                <div style="padding:20px 24px;">
                  <div class="topic-block">
                    <h4>Single-Pole Switch Wiring</h4>
                    <p>A single-pole switch controls one light or load from a single location. It interrupts the <strong>hot (black) wire</strong> only — the neutral wire passes through uninterrupted.</p>
                    <ul>
                      <li><strong>Line (hot) in</strong> → One terminal of the switch</li>
                      <li><strong>Load out</strong> → Other terminal of the switch → to the light fixture</li>
                      <li>Neutral wire runs directly from the panel to the light fixture</li>
                      <li><strong>Switch loop concept:</strong> In older wiring, two-wire cable (black + white) is used for the switch leg. The white wire is re-identified with black tape to indicate it carries hot current.</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                  <div class="topic-block" style="margin-top:18px;">
                    <h4>Duplex Outlet Wiring</h4>
                    <p>A duplex receptacle (outlet) has a <strong>brass side</strong> (hot), a <strong>silver side</strong> (neutral), and a <strong>green screw</strong> (ground). The short slot is hot; the tall slot is neutral.</p>
                    <ul>
                      <li>Black (hot) → Brass terminal</li>
                      <li>White (neutral) → Silver terminal</li>
                      <li>Green/bare (ground) → Green screw</li>
                      <li><strong>Pigtail method:</strong> When wiring multiple outlets on the same circuit, create a pigtail splice at each outlet — short wire twisted with incoming and outgoing wires, connected to outlet terminal. This prevents loss of power to subsequent outlets if one device is removed.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <div class="info-box green" style="margin-top:10px;">
                      <span class="ib-icon">&#10003;</span>
                      <div><strong>Best Practice:</strong> Always use the pigtail (splice) method rather than the back-stab/feed-through method for multiple outlet circuits. This is more reliable and conforms to good wiring practice.</div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <!-- Protective Devices -->
              <div class="card">
                <div class="section-header">
                  <div class="section-num">4</div>
                  <div>
                    <span class="session-label">Topic 4</span>
                    <h2>Protective Devices</h2>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div style="padding:20px 24px;">
                  <div class="topic-block">
                    <h4>Circuit Breaker</h4>
                    <p>A <strong>circuit breaker</strong> is a resettable automatic switch that protects an electrical circuit from overload and short circuits by interrupting current flow.</p>
                    <table class="data-table" style="margin-top:10px;">
                      <thead>
                        <tr><th>Feature</th><th>Description</th></tr>
                      </thead>
                      <tbody>
                        <tr><td><strong>Operating Principle</strong></td><td>Thermal-magnetic: bimetallic strip trips on overload; electromagnetic coil trips on short circuit</td></tr>
                        <tr><td><strong>Rating</strong></td><td>Rated in amperes (A): 15A, 20A, 30A, 60A, 100A, etc.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td><strong>Main Breaker</strong></td><td>Protects the entire panel; disconnects all branch circuits</td></tr>
                        <tr><td><strong>Branch Breaker</strong></td><td>Protects individual circuits (lighting, outlets, appliances)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td><strong>Types</strong></td><td>Single-pole (120V), Double-pole (240V), AFCI, GFCI breakers</td></tr>
                      </tbody>
                    </table>
                  </div>
                  <div class="topic-block" style="margin-top:18px;">
                    <h4>Fuse</h4>
                    <p>A <strong>fuse</strong> is a one-time overcurrent protection device. When current exceeds the rated value, a fusible element melts, opening the circuit. Unlike circuit breakers, fuses must be replaced after operation.</p>
                    <ul>
                      <li><strong>Cartridge fuse</strong> — cylindrical, used in panels and industrial equipment</li>
                      <li><strong>Plug fuse (screw-type)</strong> — threaded into a socket, used in older residential panels</li>
                      <li>Never replace a fuse with a higher rating — this defeats overcurrent protection</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                  <div class="topic-block" style="margin-top:18px;">
                    <h4>GFCI and RCD</h4>
                    <p>These devices protect against dangerous ground faults — current leaking to ground through a person.</p>
                    <table class="data-table" style="margin-top:10px;">
                      <thead>
                        <tr><th>Device</th><th>Full Name</th><th>Location</th><th>Sensitivity</th></tr>
                      </thead>
                      <tbody>
                        <tr>
                          <td><strong>GFCI</strong></td>
                          <td>Ground Fault Circuit Interrupter</td>
                          <td>Outlet-type device (replaces standard outlet)</td>
                          <td>Trips at 5 mA ground fault current</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                          <td><strong>RCD</strong></td>
                          <td>Residual Current Device</td>
                          <td>Panel-level breaker or separate din-rail device</td>
                          <td>Trips at 30 mA (general) or 5 mA (medical)</td>
                        </tr>
                      </tbody>
                    </table>
                    <div class="info-box blue" style="margin-top:12px;">
                      <span class="ib-icon">&#8505;</span>
                      <div><strong>Key Difference:</strong> GFCI is the <em>outlet-type</em> device with Test and Reset buttons on its face. RCD is the <em>panel-level</em> equivalent that protects an entire circuit or multiple circuits. Both detect ground faults as small as <strong>5 mA</strong> and trip within milliseconds. Required by PEC in bathrooms, kitchens, outdoors, garages, and near water sources.</div>
                    </div>
                    <h4 style="margin-top:16px;">GFCI Testing Procedure</h4>
                    <ol style="padding-left:20px; font-size:14px; color:var(--gray-700); line-height:1.7;">
                      <li>Press the <strong>TEST</strong> button — outlet should de-energize (plug-in light goes out)</li>
                      <li>Press the <strong>RESET</strong> button — outlet re-energizes</li>
                      <li>Test GFCI outlets monthly as recommended by NEMA</li>
                      <li>Replace GFCI if it fails to trip on TEST or fails to reset</li>
                    </ol>
                  </div>
                  <div class="topic-block" style="margin-top:18px;">
                    <h4>Safety Requirements</h4>
                    <p>When performing electrical wiring work, always follow these safety protocols:</p>
                    <ul>
                      <li><strong>PPE:</strong> Rubber insulating gloves (Class 0 minimum for 120/240V), safety glasses, insulating footwear</li>
                      <li><strong>De-energize:</strong> Always turn off and lock out/tag out the circuit breaker before working on any circuit</li>
                      <li><strong>Verify:</strong> Use a non-contact voltage tester or multimeter to confirm the circuit is de-energized before touching conductors</li>
                      <li><strong>Work alone rule:</strong> Never work alone on energized circuits; always have a qualified person present</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

            </div><!-- end s2-topics -->

