                    <span class="session-label">Topic 1</span>
                    <h2>FDAS — Components and Overview</h2>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div style="padding:20px 24px;">
                  <div class="topic-block">
                    <h4>What is FDAS?</h4>
                    <p>A <strong>Fire Detection and Alarm System (FDAS)</strong> is an integrated network of devices designed to detect fire or smoke, notify occupants of a fire emergency, and support orderly evacuation. In the Philippines, FDAS design and installation is governed by the <strong>Fire Code of the Philippines (R.A. 9514)</strong> and references <strong>NFPA 72 (National Fire Alarm and Signaling Code)</strong>.</p>
                  </div>
                  <div class="topic-block" style="margin-top:16px;">
                    <h4>FDAS Components</h4>
                    <table class="data-table">
                      <thead>
                        <tr><th>Component</th><th>Function</th><th>Location</th></tr>
                      </thead>
                      <tbody>
                        <tr>
                          <td><strong>Smoke Detector</strong></td>
                          <td>Detects products of combustion (smoke particles). Types: ionization (fast flaming fires) and photoelectric (slow smoldering fires)</td>
                          <td>Ceilings, hallways, rooms</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                          <td><strong>Heat Detector</strong></td>
                          <td>Responds to abnormal temperature rise. Types: fixed temperature (e.g., 57°C) and rate-of-rise</td>
                          <td>Kitchens, boiler rooms, dusty areas</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                          <td><strong>Manual Call Point (MCP)</strong></td>
                          <td>Manual activation device — person breaks glass or presses button to trigger alarm</td>
                          <td>Near exits, stairwells, corridors</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                          <td><strong>Fire Alarm Control Panel (FACP)</strong></td>
                          <td>Central intelligence of the FDAS — monitors all zones/devices, triggers alarms, logs events</td>
                          <td>Security room, lobby, or main entrance</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                          <td><strong>Sounders / Bells / Horns</strong></td>
                          <td>Audible alarm notification for occupants</td>
                          <td>Corridors, stairwells, throughout building</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                          <td><strong>Visual Notification (Strobe)</strong></td>
                          <td>Flashing visual alarm for hearing-impaired occupants; required in NFPA 72</td>
                          <td>Adjacent to sounders in public spaces</td>
                        </tr>
                      </tbody>
                    </table>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <!-- Conventional vs Addressable -->
              <div class="card">
                <div class="section-header">
                  <div class="section-num">2</div>
                  <div>
                    <span class="session-label">Topic 2</span>
                    <h2>Conventional vs. Addressable FDAS</h2>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div style="padding:20px 24px;">
                  <div class="topic-block">
                    <h4>System Types Comparison</h4>
                  </div>
                  <table class="data-table">
                    <thead>
                      <tr>
                        <th>Feature</th>
                        <th>Conventional FDAS</th>
                        <th>Addressable FDAS</th>
                      </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                      <tr>
                        <td><strong>Identification</strong></td>
                        <td>Identifies alarm by zone only (multiple devices per zone)</td>
                        <td>Identifies exact device address — knows which specific detector alarmed</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <td><strong>Wiring</strong></td>
                        <td>Each zone wired in a series circuit back to FACP</td>
                        <td>Loop/star topology; devices on a two-wire SLC loop</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <td><strong>Cost</strong></td>
                        <td>Lower initial cost</td>
                        <td>Higher initial cost; more efficient for large buildings</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <td><strong>Suitable For</strong></td>
                        <td>Small to medium buildings (residences, small offices)</td>
                        <td>Large buildings (hospitals, malls, high-rises)</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <td><strong>Fault Detection</strong></td>
                        <td>Identifies fault by zone; harder to pinpoint</td>
                        <td>Pinpoints exact device with fault or alarm</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <td><strong>Device Capacity</strong></td>
                        <td>Limited by number of zones on FACP</td>
                        <td>Up to 99–250+ devices per loop depending on FACP model</td>
                      </tr>
                    </tbody>
                  </table>
                  <div class="topic-block" style="margin-top:18px;">
                    <h4>Supervised Circuits and End-of-Line Resistor (EOLR)</h4>
                    <p>The FACP constantly monitors the integrity of each detection loop. This is called a <strong>supervised circuit</strong>. If a wire is cut or disconnected, the FACP immediately signals a <strong>trouble condition</strong>.</p>
                    <ul>
                      <li>An <strong>End-of-Line Resistor (EOLR)</strong> is placed at the last device on each zone or loop</li>
                      <li>The FACP measures the resistance of the circuit. Normal resistance = circuit intact; open circuit = wire broken; short circuit = devices shorted</li>
                      <li>The EOLR value is specified by the FACP manufacturer (typically 1 kΩ to 10 kΩ)</li>
                    </ul>
                    <div class="info-box gold" style="margin-top:12px;">
                      <span class="ib-icon">&#9888;</span>
                      <div><strong>Critical:</strong> The EOLR must be installed at the physically last device on the loop — NOT at the panel. Installing it at the panel would not detect wire faults between the panel and the devices.</div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                  <div class="topic-block" style="margin-top:16px;">
                    <h4>PEC and NFPA Requirements</h4>
                    <p>In the Philippines, FDAS installations must comply with:</p>
                    <ul>
                      <li><strong>NFPA 72</strong> — National Fire Alarm and Signaling Code (referenced by the Fire Code of the Philippines)</li>
                      <li><strong>RA 9514</strong> — Revised Fire Code of the Philippines</li>
                      <li>Bureau of Fire Protection (BFP) issuances and inspection requirements</li>
                      <li>All FDAS wiring to use fire-rated cables in fire-rated conduit where required by code</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

