                <div style="padding:20px 24px;">
                  <div class="topic-block">
                    <h4>CCTV System Components</h4>
                    <table class="data-table">
                      <thead>
                        <tr><th>Component</th><th>Description</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
                      </thead>
                      <tbody>
                        <tr>
                          <td><strong>Analog Camera</strong></td>
                          <td>Traditional camera; outputs composite video signal via coaxial cable</td>
                          <td>AHD, TVI, CVI, CVBS formats</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                          <td><strong>IP Camera</strong></td>
                          <td>Network-connected camera; outputs digital video over Ethernet</td>
                          <td>Higher resolution; supports PoE</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                          <td><strong>DVR</strong></td>
                          <td>Digital Video Recorder — records analog camera footage to hard drive</td>
                          <td>For analog (coaxial cable) systems</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                          <td><strong>NVR</strong></td>
                          <td>Network Video Recorder — records IP camera footage over network</td>
                          <td>For IP (UTP/Ethernet) systems</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                          <td><strong>Monitor</strong></td>
                          <td>Displays live and recorded footage; connected to DVR/NVR</td>
                          <td>BNC or HDMI connection</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                          <td><strong>Power Supply</strong></td>
                          <td>12V DC (analog cameras) or PoE switch/injector (IP cameras)</td>
                          <td>Centralized or distributed</td>
                        </tr>
                      </tbody>
                    </table>
                  </div>
                  <div class="topic-block" style="margin-top:18px;">
                    <h4>Cable Types for CCTV</h4>
                    <table class="data-table">
                      <thead>
                        <tr><th>Cable Type</th><th>Used For</th><th>Characteristics</th></tr>
                      </thead>
                      <tbody>
                        <tr>
                          <td><strong>RG59 Coaxial</strong></td>
                          <td>Analog CCTV video (standard definition)</td>
                          <td>75Ω impedance; max ~300m for standard CCTV; 95% braid shielding</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                          <td><strong>RG6 Coaxial</strong></td>
                          <td>Analog CCTV video (HD-TVI/AHD, longer runs)</td>
                          <td>75Ω impedance; lower signal loss than RG59; max ~500m</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                          <td><strong>UTP Cat5e</strong></td>
                          <td>IP cameras (standard installations)</td>
                          <td>4 twisted pairs; 100 MHz bandwidth; max 100m per segment</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                          <td><strong>UTP Cat6</strong></td>
                          <td>IP cameras (high-resolution, high-density)</td>
                          <td>4 twisted pairs; 250 MHz bandwidth; better noise rejection</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                          <td><strong>PoE (Power over Ethernet)</strong></td>
                          <td>IP cameras powered via Cat5e/Cat6</td>
                          <td>IEEE 802.3af (15W) or 802.3at (30W); power + data in one cable; max 100m</td>
                        </tr>
                      </tbody>
                    </table>
                  </div>
                  <div class="topic-block" style="margin-top:18px;">
                    <h4>BNC Connector Termination</h4>
                    <p>The <strong>BNC (Bayonet Neill-Concelman) connector</strong> is the standard connector for analog CCTV coaxial cable. The crimp-type BNC is the most common for field installation.</p>
                    <ol style="padding-left:20px; font-size:14px; color:var(--gray-700); line-height:1.8; margin-top:8px;">
                      <li><strong>Measure and strip outer jacket:</strong> Remove approximately 15mm of outer PVC jacket using a coaxial stripping tool</li>
                      <li><strong>Fold back the braided shield:</strong> Carefully fold the copper braid back over the outer jacket</li>
                      <li><strong>Strip inner insulation (dielectric):</strong> Remove approximately 5mm of the white foam dielectric to expose the center conductor</li>
                      <li><strong>Insert into BNC body:</strong> Slide the crimp ferrule onto the cable, then insert the stripped cable into the BNC body ensuring the center conductor seats into the BNC pin</li>
                      <li><strong>Crimp:</strong> Use a coaxial cable crimping tool to crimp the ferrule onto the cable body</li>
                      <li><strong>Test:</strong> Use a coaxial cable tester or multimeter to verify continuity and no short between center conductor and shield</li>
                    </ol>
                    <div class="info-box blue" style="margin-top:12px;">
                      <span class="ib-icon">&#8505;</span>
                      <div><strong>PoE Advantage:</strong> Power over Ethernet (PoE) eliminates the need for a separate power cable to each IP camera. A single Cat5e/Cat6 cable carries both the network data and 12–48V DC power from a PoE switch or injector. This significantly simplifies installation, especially for ceiling-mounted cameras far from power outlets.</div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                  <div class="topic-block" style="margin-top:18px;">
                    <h4>Camera Placement Guidelines</h4>
                    <ul>
                      <li><strong>Mounting height:</strong> 2.5 m to 3.0 m from the floor — balances coverage angle and facial recognition capability</li>
                      <li><strong>Coverage angle:</strong> Position cameras to cover entry/exit points, cashier areas, walkways, and parking areas</li>
                      <li><strong>Avoid backlight:</strong> Do not aim cameras directly at windows or bright light sources — use Wide Dynamic Range (WDR) cameras if backlight is unavoidable</li>
                      <li><strong>Overlap zones:</strong> Adjacent cameras should have 10–20% field overlap for continuous coverage</li>
                      <li><strong>IR illuminators:</strong> Use IR-capable cameras for night vision in unlit areas</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

